Container:
* a way to package application with all the necessary dependencies and configuration
* portable artifact, easily shared and moved around (Tipo um container de porto mesmo).
* Makes development and deployment more efficient.

Container port vs HOST port:
 - Multiple contianers can run on your host machine
 - Your laptop has only certain porst available

YOU CA HAVE 2 CONTAINERS ON ONE PORT, AS LONG AS YOU BIND THEM TO DIFFERENT PORTS OF YOUR MACHINE:

CONTAINER 1 : PORT 3000 -------> CONNECTED TO UR MACHINE PORT 3000
CONTAINER 2 : PORT 3000 -------> CONNECTED TO MACHINE PORT 3001

AFTER THAT YOU CAN CONNECT TO CONTAINER BY USING THE MACHINE PORT.

some-app://localhost:3001


docker pull = download image
docker run = runs it
docker -d = runs container without ocuppying the terminal
docker -p3000:6879 = delegate a host port to containers port
docker ps-a = all containers that existed on the machine
docker ps = all containers runing
docker images = gives you all images you have locally
docker logs = to see logs redis is running
docker run redis:8.6 = using redis version 8.6 specifically
docker run -d --name redis1 redis = naming redis1 the container
docker exec -it 'container id or name' /bin/bash =  get the terminal of the running container 
exit = leave the terminal



